# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: request-validation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:request-validation/data-validation] In computing, **data validation** or **input validation** is the process of ensuring data has undergone data cleansing to confirm it has data quality, that is, that it is both correct and useful.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] It uses routines, often called "validation rules", "validation constraints", or "check routines", that check for correctness, meaningfulness, and security of data that are input to the system.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] The rules may be implemented through the automated facilities of a data dictionary, or by the inclusion of explicit application program validation logic of the computer and its application.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] This is distinct from formal verification, which attempts to prove or disprove the correctness of algorithms for implementing a specification or property.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Data validation is intended to provide certain well-defined guarantees for fitness and consistency of data in an application or automated system.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Data validation rules can be defined and designed using various methodologies, and be deployed in various contexts.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Their implementation can use declarative data integrity rules, or procedure-based business rules.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] The guarantees of data validation do not necessarily include accuracy, and it is possible for data entry errors such as misspellings to be accepted as valid.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Other clerical and/or computer controls may be applied to reduce inaccuracy within a system.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] In evaluating the basics of data validation, generalizations can be made regarding the different kinds of validation according to their scope, complexity, and purpose.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Data type validation is customarily carried out on one or more simple data fields.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] The simplest kind of data type validation verifies that the individual characters provided through user input are consistent with the expected characters of one or more known primitive data types as defined in a programming language or data storage and retrieval mechanism.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] For example, an integer field may require input to use only characters 0 through 9.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Simple range and constraint validation may examine input for consistency with a minimum/maximum range, or consistency with a test for evaluating a sequence of characters, such as one or more tests against regular expressions.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] For example, a counter value may be required to be a non-negative integer, and a password may be required to meet a minimum length and contain characters from multiple categories.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Code and cross-reference validation includes operations to verify that data is consistent with one or more possibly-external rules, requirements, or collections relevant to a particular organization, context or set of underlying assumptions.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] These additional validity constraints may involve cross-referencing supplied data with a known look-up table or directory information service such as LDAP.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] For example, a user-provided country code might be required to identify a current geopolitical region.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Structured validation allows for the combination of other kinds of validation, along with more complex processing.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Such complex processing may include the testing of conditional constraints for an entire complex data object or set of process operations within a system.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Consistency validation ensures that data is logical.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] For example, the delivery date of an order can be prohibited from preceding its shipment date.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Multiple kinds of data validation are relevant to 10-digit pre-2007 ISBNs (the 2005 edition of ISO 2108 required ISBNs to have 13 digits from 2007 onwards).
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Checks to ascertain that only expected characters are present in a field.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] For example a numeric field may only allow the digits 0–9, the decimal point and perhaps a minus sign or commas.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] An e-mail address might require at least one @ sign and various other structural details.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] can be effective ways to implement such checks.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Numerical fields may be added together for all records in a batch.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] The batch total is entered and the computer checks that the total is correct, e.g., add the 'Total Cost' field of a number of transactions together.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Checks that record has a valid number of related records.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] For example, if a contact record is classified as "customer" then it must have at least one associated order (cardinality > 0).
[src:request-validation/data-validation] This type of rule can be complicated by additional conditions.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] For example, if a contact record in a payroll database is classified as "former employee" then it must not have any associated salary payments after the separation date (cardinality = 0).
[src:request-validation/data-validation] To support error detection, an extra digit is added to a number which is calculated from the other digits.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Checks fields to ensure data in these fields correspond, e.g., if expiration date is in the past then status is not "active".
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Compares data in different systems to ensure it is consistent.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Systems may represent the same data differently, in which case comparison requires transformation (e.g., one system may store customer name in a single Name field as 'Doe, John Q', while another uses First_Name 'John' and Last_Name 'Doe' and Middle_Name 'Quality').
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Checks input conformance with typed data.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] For example, an input box accepting numeric data may reject the letter 'O'.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Checks that a file with a specified name exists.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] This check is essential for programs that use file handling.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Checks that the data is in a specified format (template), e.g., dates have to be in the format YYYY-MM-DD.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Regular expressions may be used for this kind of validation.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Checks that data is present, e.g., customers may be required to have an email address.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Checks that the data is within a specified range of values, e.g., a probability must be between 0 and 1.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] tables can be linked through foreign key and primary key.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] If values in the foreign key field are not constrained by internal mechanisms, then they should be validated to ensure that the referencing table always refers to a row in the referenced table.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Looks for spelling and grammatical errors.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] This can be applied to several fields (i.e.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] A table look up check compares data to a collection of allowed values.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Enforcement action typically rejects the data entry request and requires the input actor to make a change that brings the data into compliance.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] This is most suitable for interactive use, where a real person is sitting on the computer and making entry.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] It also works well for batch upload, where a file input may be rejected and a set of messages sent back to the input source for why the data is rejected.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Another form of enforcement action involves automatically changing the data and saving a conformant version instead of the original version.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] This is most suitable for cosmetic change.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] For example, converting an [all-caps] entry to a [Pascal case] entry does not need user input.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] An inappropriate use of automatic enforcement would be in situations where the enforcement leads to loss of business information.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] For example, saving a truncated comment if the length is longer than expected.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] This is not typically a good thing since it may result in loss of significant data.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Advisory actions typically allow data to be entered unchanged but sends a message to the source actor indicating those validation issues that were encountered.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] This is most suitable for non-interactive system, for systems where the change is not business critical, for cleansing steps of existing data and for verification steps of an entry process.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Verification actions are special cases of advisory actions.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] In this case, the source actor is asked to verify that this data is what they would really want to enter, in the light of a suggestion to the contrary.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Here, the check step suggests an alternative (e.g., a check of a mailing address returns a different way of formatting that address or suggests a different address altogether).
[src:request-validation/data-validation] You would want in this case, to give the user the option of accepting the recommendation or keeping their version.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] This is not a strict validation process, by design and is useful for capturing addresses to a new location or to a location that is not yet supported by the validation databases.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Even in cases where data validation did not find any issues, providing a log of validations that were conducted and their results is important.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Failures or omissions in data validation can lead to data corruption or a security vulnerability.
[src:request-validation/data-validation] Data validation checks that data are fit for purpose, valid, sensible, reasonable and secure before they are processed.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:request-validation/json-schema] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:request-validation/json-schema] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:request-validation/json-schema] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:request-validation/json-schema] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:request-validation/json-schema] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:request-validation/json-schema] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:request-validation/json-schema] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:request-validation/json-schema] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:request-validation/json-schema] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] A **regular expression** (shortened as **regex** or **regexp**), sometimes referred to as a **rational expression**, is a sequence of characters that specifies a match pattern in text.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Usually such patterns are used by string-searching algorithms for "find" or "find and replace" operations on strings, or for input validation.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Regular expression techniques are developed in theoretical computer science and formal language theory.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The concept of regular expressions began in the 1950s, when the American mathematician Stephen Cole Kleene formalized the concept of a regular language.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] They came into common use with Unix text-processing utilities.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Different syntaxes for writing regular expressions have existed since the 1980s, one being the POSIX standard and another, widely used, being the Perl syntax.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions are used in search engines, in search and replace dialogs of word processors and text editors, in text processing utilities such as sed and AWK, and in lexical analysis.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions are supported in many programming languages.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Library implementations are often called an "engine", and many of these are available for reuse.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions originated in 1951, when mathematician Stephen Cole Kleene described regular languages using his mathematical notation called *regular events*.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] These arose in theoretical computer science, in the subfields of automata theory (models of computation) and the description and classification of formal languages, motivated by Kleene's attempt to describe early artificial neural networks.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions entered popular use from 1968 in two uses: pattern matching in a text editor and lexical analysis in a compiler.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Among the first appearances of regular expressions in program form was when Ken Thompson built Kleene's notation into the editor QED as a means to match patterns in text files.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] For speed, Thompson implemented regular expression matching by just-in-time compilation (JIT) to IBM 7094 code on the Compatible Time-Sharing System, an important early example of JIT compilation.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Around the same time that Thompson developed QED, a group of researchers including Douglas T.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Ross implemented a tool based on regular expressions that is used for lexical analysis in compiler design.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Many variations of these original forms of regular expressions were used in Unix programs at Bell Labs in the 1970s, including lex, sed, AWK, and expr, and in other programs such as vi, and Emacs (which has its own, incompatible syntax and behavior).
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Regexes were subsequently adopted by a wide range of programs, with these early forms standardized in the POSIX.2 standard in 1992.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] In the 1980s, the more complicated regexes arose in Perl, which originally derived from a regex library written by Henry Spencer (1986), who later wrote an implementation for Tcl called *Advanced Regular Expressions*.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The Tcl library is a hybrid NFA/DFA implementation with improved performance characteristics.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Software projects that have adopted Spencer's Tcl regular expression implementation include PostgreSQL.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Perl later expanded on Spencer's original library to add many new features.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Part of the effort in the design of Raku (formerly named Perl 6) is to improve Perl's regex integration, and to increase their scope and capabilities to allow the definition of parsing expression grammars.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The result is a mini-language called Raku rules, which are used to define Raku grammar as well as provide a tool to programmers in the language.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] These rules maintain existing features of Perl 5.x regexes, but also allow BNF-style definition of a recursive descent parser via sub-rules.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The use of regexes in structured information standards for document and database modeling started in the 1960s and expanded in the 1980s when industry standards like ISO SGML (precursored by ANSI "GCA 101-1983") consolidated.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The kernel of the structure specification language standards consists of regexes.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Its use is evident in the DTD element group syntax.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Prior to the use of regular expressions, many search languages allowed simple wildcards, for example "*" to match any sequence of characters, and "?" to match a single character.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Relics of this can be found today in the glob syntax for filenames, and in the SQL `LIKE` operator.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Starting in 1997, Philip Hazel developed PCRE (Perl Compatible Regular Expressions), which attempts to closely mimic Perl's regex functionality and is used by many modern tools including PHP and Apache HTTP Server.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Today, regexes are widely supported in programming languages, text processing programs (particularly lexers), advanced text editors, and some other programs.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Regex support is part of the standard library of many programming languages, including Java and Python, and is built into the syntax of others, including Perl and ECMAScript.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The phrase *regular expressions*, or *regexes*, is often used to mean the specific, standard textual syntax for representing patterns for matching text, as distinct from the mathematical notation described below.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Each character in a regular expression (that is, each character in the string describing its pattern) is either a metacharacter, having a special meaning, or a regular character that has a literal meaning.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] For example, in the regex `b.`, 'b' is a literal character that matches just 'b', while '.' is a metacharacter that matches every character except a newline.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Therefore, this regex matches, for example, 'b%', or 'bx', or 'b5'.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Together, metacharacters and literal characters can be used to identify text of a given pattern or process a number of instances of it.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Pattern matches may vary from a precise equality to a very general similarity, as controlled by the metacharacters.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] For example, `.` is a very general pattern, `[a-z]` (match all lowercase letters from 'a' to 'z') is less general and `b` is a precise pattern (matches just 'b').
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The metacharacter syntax is designed specifically to represent prescribed targets in a concise and flexible way to direct the automation of text processing of a variety of input data, in a form easy to type using a standard ASCII keyboard.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] A very simple case of a regular expression in this syntax is to locate a word spelled two different ways in a text editor; for example, the regular expression `seriali[sz]e` matches both "serialise" and "serialize".
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Wildcard characters also achieve this, but are more limited in what they can pattern, as they have fewer metacharacters and a simple language-base.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The usual context of wildcard characters is in globbing similar names in a list of files, whereas regexes are usually employed in applications that pattern-match text strings in general.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] For example, the regex `^[ \t]+|[ \t]+$` matches excess whitespace at the beginning or end of a line.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] A **regex processor** translates a regular expression in the above syntax into an internal representation that can be executed and matched against a string representing the text being searched in.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] One possible approach is the Thompson's construction algorithm to construct a nondeterministic finite automaton (NFA), which is then made deterministic and the resulting deterministic finite automaton (DFA) is run on the target text string to recognize substrings that match the regular expression.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The picture shows the NFA scheme `*N*(*s**)` obtained from the regular expression `*s**`, where *s* denotes a simpler regular expression in turn, which has already been recursively translated to the NFA *N*(*s*).
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] A regular expression, often called a *pattern*, specifies a set of strings required for a particular purpose.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] A simple way to specify a finite set of strings is to list its elements or members.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] However, there are often more concise ways: for example, the set containing the three strings "Handel", "Händel", and "Haendel" can be specified by the pattern `H(ä|ae?)ndel`; we say that this pattern *matches* each of the three strings.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] However, there can be many ways to write a regular expression for the same set of strings: for example, `(Hän|Han|Haen)del` also specifies the same set of three strings in this example.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Most formalisms provide the following operations to construct regular expressions.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] are equivalent patterns which both describe the set of "gray" or "grey".
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] , character, or group) specifies how many times the preceding element is allowed to repeat.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] matches any string that contains an "a", and then any character and then "b".
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] matches any string that contains an "a", and then the character "b" at some later point.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] These constructions can be combined to form arbitrarily complex expressions, much like one can construct arithmetical expressions from numbers and the operations +, −, ×, and ÷.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The precise syntax for regular expressions varies among tools and with context; more detail is given in § Syntax.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions describe regular languages in formal language theory.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] They have the same expressive power as regular grammars.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] But the language of regular expressions itself, is context-free language.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions consist of constants, which denote sets of strings, and operator symbols, which denote operations over these sets.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The following definition is standard, and found as such in most textbooks on formal language theory.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] To avoid parentheses, it is assumed that the Kleene star has the highest priority followed by concatenation, then alternation.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] If there is no ambiguity, then parentheses may be omitted.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] For example, `(ab)c` can be written as `abc`, and `a|(b(c*))` can be written as `a|bc*`.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Many textbooks use the symbols ∪, +, or ∨ for alternation instead of the vertical bar.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The derivative of a regular expression can be defined using the Brzozowski derivative.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The formal definition of regular expressions is minimal on purpose, and avoids defining `?` and `+`—these can be expressed as follows: `a+`=`aa*`, and `a?`=`(a|ε)`.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Sometimes the complement operator is added, to give a *generalized regular expression*; here *Rc* matches all strings over Σ* that do not match *R*.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] In principle, the complement operator is redundant, because it does not grant any more expressive power.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] However, it can make a regular expression much more concise—eliminating a single complement operator can cause a double exponential blow-up of its length.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions in this sense can express the regular languages, exactly the class of languages accepted by deterministic finite automata.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] There is, however, a significant difference in compactness.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Some classes of regular languages can only be described by deterministic finite automata whose size grows exponentially in the size of the shortest equivalent regular expressions.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The standard example here is the languages *Lk* consisting of all strings over the alphabet {*a*,*b*} whose *k*th-from-last letter equals *a*.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] On the one hand, a regular expression describing *L*4 is given by $(a\mid b)^{*}a(a\mid b)(a\mid b)(a\mid b)$ .
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] On the other hand, it is known that every deterministic finite automaton accepting the language *Lk* must have at least 2*k* states.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Luckily, there is a simple mapping from regular expressions to the more general nondeterministic finite automata (NFAs) that does not lead to such a blowup in size; for this reason NFAs are often used as alternative representations of regular languages.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] NFAs are a simple variation of the type-3 grammars of the Chomsky hierarchy.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] In the opposite direction, there are many languages easily described by a DFA that are not easily described by a regular expression.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] For instance, determining the validity of a given ISBN requires computing the remainder of an integer modulo 11, and can be easily implemented with an 11-state DFA.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] However, converting it to a regular expression results in a 2.14-megabyte file.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Given a regular expression, Thompson's construction algorithm computes an equivalent nondeterministic finite automaton.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] A conversion in the opposite direction is achieved by Kleene's algorithm.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Finally, many real-world "regular expression" engines implement features that cannot be described by the regular expressions in the sense of formal language theory; rather, they implement *regexes*.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] As seen in many of the examples above, there is more than one way to construct a regular expression to achieve the same results.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] It is possible to write an algorithm that, for two given regular expressions, decides whether the described languages are equal; the algorithm reduces each expression to a minimal deterministic finite state machine, and determines whether they are isomorphic (equivalent).
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] More generally, an equation *E*=*F* between regular-expression terms with variables holds if, and only if, its instantiation with different variables replaced by different symbol constants holds.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Every regular expression can be written solely in terms of the Kleene star and set unions over finite words.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] This is a surprisingly difficult problem.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] As simple as the regular expressions are, there is no method to systematically rewrite them to some normal form.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The lack of axiom in the past led to the star height problem.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] In 1991, Dexter Kozen axiomatized regular expressions as a Kleene algebra, using equational and Horn clause axioms.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Already in 1964, Redko had proved that no finite set of purely equational axioms can characterize the algebra of regular languages.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] A regex *pattern* matches a target *string*.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The pattern is composed of a sequence of *atoms*.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] An atom is a single point within the regex pattern which it tries to match to the target string.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The simplest atom is a literal, but grouping parts of the pattern to match an atom will require using `( )` as metacharacters.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] A match is made, not when all the atoms of the string are matched, but rather when all the pattern atoms in the regex have matched.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The idea is to make a small pattern of characters stand for a large number of possible strings, rather than compiling a large list of all the literal possibilities.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Depending on the regex processor there are about fourteen metacharacters, characters that may or may not have their literal character meaning, depending on context, or whether they are "escaped", i.e. preceded by an escape sequence, in this case, the backslash `\`.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The usual characters that become metacharacters when escaped are `dswDSW` and `N`.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] When entering a regex in a programming language, they may be represented as a usual string literal, hence usually quoted; this is common in C, Java, and Python for instance, where the regex `re` is entered as `"re"`.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] However, they are often written with slashes as delimiters, as in `/re/` for the regex `re`.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] A similar convention is used in sed, where search and replace is given by `s/re/replacement/` and patterns can be joined with a comma to specify a range of lines as in `/re1/,/re2/`.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] This notation is particularly well known due to its use in Perl, where it forms part of the syntax distinct from normal string literals.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] In some cases, such as sed and Perl, alternative delimiters can be used to avoid collision with contents, and to avoid having to escape occurrences of the delimiter character in the contents.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] For example, in sed the command `s,/,X,` will replace a `/` with an `X`, using commas as delimiters.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The IEEE POSIX standard has three sets of compliance: **BRE** (Basic Regular Expressions), **ERE** (Extended Regular Expressions), and **SRE** (Simple Regular Expressions).
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] SRE is deprecated, in favor of BRE, as both provide backward compatibility.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The subsection below covering the *character classes* applies to both BRE and ERE.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] ERE adds `?`, `+`, and `|`, and it removes the need to escape the metacharacters `( )` and `{ }`, which are *required* in BRE.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Furthermore, as long as the POSIX standard syntax for regexes is adhered to, there can be, and often is, additional syntax to serve specific (yet POSIX compliant) applications.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Although POSIX.2 leaves some implementation specifics undefined, BRE and ERE provide a "standard" which has since been adopted as the default syntax of many tools, where the choice of BRE or ERE modes is usually a supported option.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] For example, GNU `grep` has the following options: "`grep -E`" for ERE, and "`grep -G`" for BRE (the default), and "`grep -P`" for Perl regexes.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Perl regexes have become a de facto standard, having a rich and powerful set of atomic expressions.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Perl has no "basic" or "extended" levels.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] As in POSIX EREs, `( )` and `{ }` are treated as metacharacters unless escaped; other metacharacters are known to be literal or symbolic based on context alone.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Additional functionality includes lazy matching, backreferences, named capture groups, and recursive patterns.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] In the POSIX standard, Basic Regular Syntax (**BRE**) requires that the metacharacters `( )` and `{ }` be designated `\(\)` and `\{\}`, whereas Extended Regular Syntax (**ERE**) does not.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] According to Russ Cox, the POSIX specification requires ambiguous subexpressions to be handled in a way different from Perl's.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The committee replaced Perl's rules with one that is simple to explain, but the new "simple" rules are actually more complex to implement: they were incompatible with pre-existing tooling and made it essentially impossible to define a "lazy match" (see below) extension.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] As a result, very few programs actually implement the POSIX subexpression rules (even when they implement other parts of the POSIX syntax).
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The meaning of metacharacters escaped with a backslash is reversed for some characters in the POSIX Extended Regular Expression (**ERE**) syntax.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] With this syntax, a backslash causes the metacharacter to be treated as a literal character.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] POSIX Extended Regular Expressions can often be used with modern Unix utilities by including the command line flag *-E*.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The character class is the most basic regex concept after a literal match.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] It makes one small sequence of characters match a larger set of characters.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] For example, `[A-Z]` could stand for any uppercase letter in the English alphabet, and `\d` could mean any digit.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Character classes apply to both POSIX levels.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] When specifying a range of characters, such as `[a-Z]` (i.e. lowercase *`a`* to uppercase *`Z`*), the computer's locale settings determine the contents by the numeric ordering of the character encoding.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] They could store digits in that sequence, or the ordering could be *abc...zABC...Z*, or *aAbBcC...zZ*.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] So the POSIX standard defines a character class, which will be known by the regex processor installed.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] POSIX character classes can only be used within bracket expressions.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] For example, `[[:upper:]ab]` matches the uppercase letters and lowercase "a" and "b".
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] An additional non-POSIX class understood by some tools is `[:word:]`, which is usually defined as `[:alnum:]` plus underscore.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] This reflects the fact that in many programming languages these are the characters that may be used in identifiers.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Note that what the POSIX regex standards call *character classes* are commonly referred to as *POSIX character classes* in other regex flavors which support them.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] With most other regex flavors, the term *character class* is used to describe what POSIX calls *bracket expressions*.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Because of its expressive power and (relative) ease of reading, many other utilities and programming languages have adopted syntax similar to Perl's—for example, Java, JavaScript, Julia, Python, Ruby, Qt, Microsoft's .NET Framework, and XML Schema.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Some languages and tools such as Boost and PHP support multiple regex flavors.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Perl-derivative regex implementations are not identical and usually implement a subset of features found in Perl 5.0, released in 1994.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Perl sometimes does incorporate features initially found in other languages.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] For example, Perl 5.10 implements syntactic extensions originally developed in PCRE and Python.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] In Python and some other implementations (e.g.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Java), the three common quantifiers (`*`, `+`, and `?`) are greedy by default because they match as many characters as possible.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] matches the entire line (because the entire line begins and ends with a double-quote) instead of matching only the first part, `"Ganymede,"`.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The aforementioned quantifiers may, however, be made *lazy* or *minimal* or *reluctant*, matching as few characters as possible, by appending a question mark: `".+?"` matches only `"Ganymede,"`.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] matches the entire line, the regex `".*+"` does *not match at all*, because `.*+` consumes the entire input, including the final `"`.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Thus, possessive quantifiers are most useful with negated character classes, e.g.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] `"[^"]*+"`, which matches `"Ganymede,"` when applied to the same string.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Another common extension serving the same function is atomic grouping, which disables backtracking for a parenthesized group.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] For example, while ^(wi|w)i$ matches both wi and wii, ^(?>wi|w)i$ only matches wii because the engine is forbidden from backtracking and so cannot try setting the group to "w" after matching "wi".
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Possessive quantifiers are easier to implement than greedy and lazy quantifiers, and are typically more efficient at runtime.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] IETF RFC 9485 describes "I-Regexp: An Interoperable Regular Expression Format".
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] It specifies a limited subset of regular-expression idioms designed to be interoperable, i.e. produce the same effect, in a large number of regular-expression libraries.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] I-Regexp is also limited to matching, i.e. providing a true or false match between a regular expression and a given piece of text.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Thus, it lacks advanced features such as capture groups, lookahead, and backreferences.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Many features found in virtually all modern regular expression libraries provide an expressive power that exceeds the regular languages.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] For example, many implementations allow grouping subexpressions with parentheses and recalling the value they match in the same expression (*backreferences*).
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] This means that, among other things, a pattern can match strings of repeated words like "papa" or "WikiWiki", called *squares* in formal language theory.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The pattern for these strings is `(.+)\1`.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The language of squares is not regular, nor is it context-free, due to the pumping lemma.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] However, pattern matching with an unbounded number of backreferences, as supported by numerous modern tools, is still context sensitive.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The general problem of matching any number of backreferences is NP-complete, and the execution time for known algorithms grows exponentially by the number of backreference groups used.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] However, many tools, libraries, and engines that provide such constructions still use the term *regular expression* for their patterns.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] This has led to a nomenclature where the term regular expression has different meanings in formal language theory and pattern matching.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] For this reason, some people have taken to using the term *regex*, *regexp*, or simply *pattern* to describe the latter.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Other features not found in describing regular languages include assertions.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] These include the ubiquitous `^` and `$`, used since at least 1970, as well as some more sophisticated extensions like lookaround that appeared in 1994.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Lookarounds define the surrounding of a match and do not spill into the match itself, a feature only relevant for the use case of string searching.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Some of them can be simulated in a regular language by treating the surroundings as a part of the language as well.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The look-ahead assertions `(?=...)` and `(?!...)` have been attested since at least 1994, starting with Perl 5.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The lookbehind assertions `(?<=...)` and `(?<!...)` are attested since 1997 in a commit by Ilya Zakharevich to Perl 5.005.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] There are at least three different algorithms that decide whether and how a given regex matches a string.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The oldest and fastest relies on a result in formal language theory that allows every nondeterministic finite automaton (NFA) to be transformed into a deterministic finite automaton (DFA).
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The DFA can be constructed explicitly and then run on the resulting input string one symbol at a time.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Constructing the DFA for a regular expression of size *m* has the time and memory cost of *O*(2*m*), but it can be run on a string of size *n* in time *O*(*n*).
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Note that the size of the expression is the size after abbreviations, such as numeric quantifiers, have been expanded.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] An alternative approach is to simulate the NFA directly, essentially building each DFA state on demand and then discarding it at the next step.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] This keeps the DFA implicit and avoids the exponential construction cost, but running cost rises to *O*(*mn*).
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The explicit approach is called the DFA algorithm and the implicit approach the NFA algorithm.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Adding caching to the NFA algorithm is often called the "lazy DFA" algorithm, or just the DFA algorithm without making a distinction.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] These algorithms are fast, but using them for recalling grouped subexpressions, lazy quantification, and similar features is tricky.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Modern implementations include the re1-re2-sregex family based on Cox's code.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] The third algorithm is to match the pattern against the input string by backtracking.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] This algorithm is commonly called NFA, but this terminology can be confusing.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Its running time can be exponential, which simple implementations exhibit when matching against expressions like `(a|aa)*b` that contain both alternation and unbounded quantification and force the algorithm to consider an exponentially increasing number of sub-cases.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] This behavior can cause a security problem called Regular expression Denial of Service (ReDoS).
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Although backtracking implementations only give an exponential guarantee in the worst case, they provide much greater flexibility and expressive power.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] For example, any implementation which allows the use of backreferences, or implements the various extensions introduced by Perl, must include some kind of backtracking.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Some implementations try to provide the best of both algorithms by first running a fast DFA algorithm, and revert to a potentially slower backtracking algorithm only when a backreference is encountered during the match.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] GNU grep (and the underlying gnulib DFA) uses such a strategy.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Sublinear runtime algorithms have been achieved using Boyer-Moore (BM) based algorithms and related DFA optimization techniques such as the reverse scan.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] GNU grep, which supports a wide variety of POSIX syntaxes and extensions, uses BM for a first-pass prefiltering, and then uses an implicit DFA.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Wu agrep, which implements approximate matching, combines the prefiltering into the DFA in BDM (backward DAWG matching).
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] NR-grep's BNDM extends the BDM technique with Shift-Or bit-level parallelism.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] A few theoretical alternatives to backtracking for backreferences exist, and their "exponents" are tamer in that they are only related to the number of backreferences, a fixed property of some regexp languages such as POSIX.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] One naive method that duplicates a non-backtracking NFA for each backreference note has a complexity of ⁠ ${\mathrm {O} }(n^{2k+2})$ ⁠ time and ⁠ ${\mathrm {O} }(n^{2k+1})$ ⁠ space for a haystack of length n and k backreferences in the RegExp.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Theoretical work based on memory automata gives a tighter bound based on "active" variable nodes used, and a polynomial possibility for some backreferenced regexps.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] In theoretical terms, any token set can be matched by regular expressions as long as it is pre-defined.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] In terms of historical implementations, regexes were originally written to use ASCII characters as their token set though regex libraries have supported numerous other character sets.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Many modern regex engines offer at least some support for Unicode.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] In most respects it makes no difference what the character set is, but some issues do arise when extending regexes to support Unicode.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p01] Most general-purpose programming languages support regex capabilities, either natively or via libraries.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] Regexes are useful in a wide variety of text processing tasks, and more generally string processing, where the data need not be textual.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] Common applications include data validation, data scraping (especially web scraping), data wrangling, simple parsing, the production of syntax highlighting systems, and many other tasks.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] Some high-end desktop publishing software has the ability to use regexes to automatically apply text styling, saving the person doing the layout from laboriously doing this by hand for anything that can be matched by a regex.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] For example, by defining a character style that makes text into small caps and then using the regex `[A-Z]{4,}` to apply that style, any word of four or more consecutive capital letters will be automatically rendered as small caps instead.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] While regexes would be useful on Internet search engines, processing them across the entire database could consume excessive computer resources depending on the complexity and design of the regex.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] Although in many cases system administrators can run regex-based queries internally, most search engines do not offer regex support to the public.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] Notable exceptions include Google Code Search and Exalead.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] However, Google Code Search was shut down in January 2012.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] The specific syntax rules vary depending on the specific implementation, programming language, or library in use.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] Additionally, the functionality of regex implementations can vary between versions.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] Because regexes can be difficult to both explain and understand without examples, interactive websites for testing regexes are a useful resource for learning regexes by experimentation.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] This section provides a basic description of some of the properties of regexes by way of illustration.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] The following conventions are used in the examples.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] Standard POSIX regular expressions are different.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] Unless otherwise indicated, the following examples conform to the Perl programming language, release 5.8.8, January 31, 2006.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] This means that other implementations may lack support for some parts of the syntax shown here (e.g. basic vs. extended regex, `\( \)` vs.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] The syntax and conventions used in these examples coincide with that of other programming environments as well.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] Regular expressions can often be created ("induced" or "learned") based on a set of example strings.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] This is known as the induction of regular languages and is part of the general problem of grammar induction in computational learning theory.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] Formally, given examples of strings in a regular language, and perhaps also given examples of strings *not* in that regular language, it is possible to induce a grammar for the language, i.e., a regular expression that generates that language.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] Not all regular languages can be induced in this way (see language identification in the limit), but many can.
[src:request-validation/regular-expression-p02] For example, the set of examples {1, 10, 100}, and negative set (of counterexamples) {11, 1001, 101, 0} can be used to induce the regular expression 1⋅0* (1 followed by zero or more 0s).
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] An **XML Schema** is a description of a type of XML document, typically expressed in terms of constraints on the structure and content of documents of that type, above and beyond the basic syntactical constraints imposed by XML itself.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] There are languages developed specifically to express XML Schemas.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] The document type definition (DTD) language, which is native to the XML specification, is a schema language that is of relatively limited capability, but that also has other uses in XML aside from the expression of schemas.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Two more expressive XML Schema languages in widespread use are XML Schema (with a capital *S*) and RELAX NG.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] The mechanism for associating an XML document with a schema varies according to the schema language.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] The association may be achieved via markup within the XML document itself, or via some external means.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] The XML Schema Definition is commonly referred to as XSD.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] The process of checking to see if an XML document conforms to a schema is called validation, which is separate from XML's core concept of syntactic well-formedness.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] All XML documents must be well-formed, but it is not required that a document be valid unless the XML parser is "validating", in which case the document is also checked for conformance with its associated schema.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] DTD-validating parsers are most common, but some support XML Schema or RELAX NG as well.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Validation of an instance document against a schema can be regarded as a conceptually separate operation from XML parsing.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] In practice, however, many schema validators are integrated with an XML parser.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] There are several different languages available for specifying an XML Schema.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Each language has its strengths and weaknesses.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] The primary purpose of a schema language is to specify what the structure of an XML document can be.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] This means which elements can reside in which other elements, which attributes are and are not legal to have on a particular element, and so forth.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] A schema is analogous to a grammar for a language; a schema defines what the vocabulary for the language may be and what a valid "sentence" is.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] The main ones (see also the ISO 19757's endorsed languages) are described below.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Though there are a number of schema languages available, the primary three languages are Document Type Definitions, W3C XML Schema, and RELAX NG.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Each language has its own advantages and disadvantages.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] DTDs are perhaps the most widely supported schema language for XML.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Because DTDs are one of the earliest schema languages for XML, defined before XML even had namespace support, they are widely supported.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Internal DTDs are often supported in XML processors; external DTDs are less often supported, but only slightly.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Most large XML parsers, ones that support multiple XML technologies, will provide support for DTDs as well.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] XSD schemas are conventionally written as XML documents, so familiar editing and transformation tools can be used.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] As well as validation, XSD allows XML instances to be annotated with type information (the Post-Schema-Validation Infoset (PSVI)) which is designed to make manipulation of the XML instance easier in application programs.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] This may be by mapping the XSD-defined types to types in a programming language such as Java ("data binding") or by enriching the type system of XML processing languages such as XSLT and XQuery (known as "schema-awareness").
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] RELAX NG and W3C XML Schema allow for similar mechanisms of specificity.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Both allow for a degree of modularity in their languages, including, for example, splitting the schema into multiple files.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] And both of them are, or can be, defined in an XML language.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] RELAX NG does not have any analog to PSVI.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Unlike W3C XML Schema, RELAX NG was designed so that validation and augmentation (adding type information and default values) are separate.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] W3C XML Schema has a formal mechanism for attaching a schema to an XML document, while RELAX NG intentionally avoids such mechanisms for security and interoperability reasons.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] RELAX NG has no ability to apply default attribute data to an element's list of attributes (i.e., changing the XML info set), while W3C XML Schema does.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Again, this design is intentional and is to separate validation and augmentation.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] W3C XML Schema has a rich "simple type" system built-in (xs:number, xs:date, etc., plus derivation of custom types), while RELAX NG has an extremely simplistic one because it is meant to use type libraries developed independently of RELAX NG, rather than grow its own.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] In practice it is common for a RELAX NG schema to use the predefined "simple types" and "restrictions" (pattern, maxLength, etc.) of W3C XML Schema.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] In W3C XML Schema a specific number or range of repetitions of patterns can be expressed whereas it is practically not possible to specify at all in RELAX NG (<oneOrMore> or <zeroOrMore>).
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] W3C XML Schema is complex and hard to learn, although that is partially because it tries to do more than mere validation (see PSVI).
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Although being written in XML is an advantage, it is also a disadvantage in some ways.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] The W3C XML Schema language, in particular, can be quite verbose, while a DTD can be terse and relatively easily editable.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Likewise, WXS's formal mechanism for associating a document with a schema can pose a potential security problem.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] For WXS validators that will follow a URI to an arbitrary online location, there is the potential for reading something malicious from the other side of the stream.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] W3C XML Schema does not implement most of the DTD ability to provide data elements to a document.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Although W3C XML Schema's ability to add default attributes to elements is an advantage, it is a disadvantage in some ways as well.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] It means that an XML file may not be usable in the absence of its schema, even if the document would validate against that schema.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] In effect, all users of such an XML document must also implement the W3C XML Schema specification, thus ruling out minimalist or older XML parsers.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] It can also slow down the processing of the document, as the processor must potentially download and process a second XML file (the schema); however, a schema would normally then be cached, so the cost comes only on the first use.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] WXS support exists in a number of large XML parsing packages.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Xerces and the .NET Framework's Base Class Library both provide support for WXS validation.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] RELAX NG provides for most of the advantages that W3C XML Schema does over DTDs.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] While the language of RELAX NG can be written in XML, it also has an equivalent form that is much more like a DTD, but with greater specifying power.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] This form is known as the compact syntax.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Tools can easily convert between these forms with no loss of features or even commenting.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Even arbitrary elements specified between RELAX NG XML elements can be converted into the compact form.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] RELAX NG provides very strong support for unordered content.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] That is, it allows the schema to state that a sequence of patterns may appear in any order.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] RELAX NG also allows for non-deterministic content models.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] When the validator encounters something that matches the "odd" pattern, it is unknown whether this is the optional last "odd" reference or simply one in the zeroOrMore sequence without looking ahead at the data.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] RELAX NG allows this kind of specification.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] W3C XML Schema requires all of its sequences to be fully deterministic, so mechanisms like the above must be either specified in a different way or omitted altogether.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] RELAX NG allows attributes to be treated as elements in content models.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] This block states that the element "some_element" must have an attribute named "has_name".
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] This attribute can only take true or false as values, and if it is true, the first child element of the element must be "name", which stores text.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] If "name" did not need to be the first element, then the choice could be wrapped in an "interleave" element along with other elements.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] The order of the specification of attributes in RELAX NG has no meaning, so this block need not be the first block in the element definition.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] W3C XML Schema cannot specify such a dependency between the content of an attribute and child elements.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] RELAX NG's specification only lists two built-in types (string and token), but it allows for the definition of many more.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] In theory, the lack of a specific list allows a processor to support data types that are very problem-domain specific.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Most RELAX NG schemas can be algorithmically converted into W3C XML Schemas and even DTDs (except when using RELAX NG features not supported by those languages, as above).
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] As such, RELAX NG can be used as a normative version of the schema, and the user can convert it to other forms for tools that do not support RELAX NG.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Most of RELAX NG's disadvantages are covered under the section on W3C XML Schema's advantages over RELAX NG.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Though RELAX NG's ability to support user-defined data types is useful, it comes at the disadvantage of only having two data types that the user can rely upon.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Which, in theory, means that using a RELAX NG schema across multiple validators requires either providing those user-defined data types to that validator or using only the two basic types.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] In practice, however, most RELAX NG processors support the W3C XML Schema set of data types.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Schematron is a fairly unusual schema language.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Unlike the main three, it defines an XML file's syntax as a list of XPath-based rules.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] If the document passes these rules, then it is valid.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Because of its rule-based nature, Schematron's specificity is very strong.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] It can require that the content of an element be controlled by one of its siblings.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] It can also request or require that the root element, regardless of what element that happens to be, have specific attributes.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] It can even specify required relationships between multiple XML files.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] While Schematron is good at relational constructs, its ability to specify the basic structure of a document, that is, which elements can go where, results in a very verbose schema.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] The typical way to solve this is to combine Schematron with RELAX NG or W3C XML Schema.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] There are several schema processors available for both languages that support this combined form.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] This allows Schematron rules to specify additional constraints to the structure defined by W3C XML Schema or RELAX NG.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Schematron's reference implementation is actually an XSLT transformation that transforms the Schematron document into an XSLT that validates the XML file.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] As such, Schematron's potential toolset is any XSLT processor, though libxml2 provides an implementation that does not require XSLT.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Sun Microsystems's Multiple Schema Validator for Java has an add-on that allows it to validate RELAX NG schemas that have embedded Schematron rules.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] This is not technically a schema language.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Its sole purpose is to direct parts of documents to individual schemas based on the namespace of the encountered elements.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] An NRL is merely a list of XML namespaces and a path to a schema that each corresponds to.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] This allows each schema to be concerned with only its own language definition, and the NRL file routes the schema validator to the correct schema file based on the namespace of that element.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] This XML format is schema-language agnostic and works for just about any schema language.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Capitalization in the *schema* word: there is some confusion as to when to use the capitalized spelling "Schema" and when to use the lowercase spelling.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] The lowercase form is a generic term and may refer to any type of schema, including DTD, XML Schema (aka XSD), RELAX NG, or others, and should always be written using lowercase except when appearing at the start of a sentence.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] The form "Schema" (capitalized) in common use in the XML community always refers to W3C XML Schema.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] The focus of the *schema* definition is structure and some semantics of documents.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] However, schema design, just like design of databases, computer program, and other formal constructs, also involve many considerations of style, convention, and readability.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Extensive discussions of schema design issues can be found in (for example) Maler (1995) and DeRose (1997).
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] One obvious consideration is that tags and attribute names should use consistent conventions.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] but others use underscores to separate parts of names, or other conventions.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] As in other formal languages, good choices of names can help understanding, even though the names per se have no formal significance.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Naming the appropriate tag "chapter" rather than "tag37" is a help to the reader.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] At the same time, this brings in issues of the choice of natural language.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] documents will probably use the same language for element and attribute names, since that will be the language common to editors and readers.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Some information can "fit" readily in either an element or an attribute.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Because attributes cannot contain elements in XML, this question only arises for components that have no further sub-structure that XML needs to be aware of (attributes do support multiple tokens, such as multiple IDREF values, which can be considered a slight exception).
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Attributes typically represent information associated with the entirety of the element on which they occur, while sub-elements introduce a new scope of their own.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] , ensure that all "text content" (roughly, any part that one would speak if reading the document aloud) occurs as text, and never in attributes.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] Second, information like stage directions in plays, verse numbers in Classical and Scriptural works, and correction or normalization of spelling in transcribed works, all pose issues of interpretation that schema designers for such genres must consider.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] and modularization control over namespaces) and recommend reuse where practical.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] schemas are also re-used in an extraordinary variety of other schemas.
[src:request-validation/xml-schema] express formally semantic, only structure and data-types.
